ssia as case studies), but also includes articles on Germany, Japan and Turkey, which provide a much needed comparative dimension. The main focus is on new conditions of political utilization of history in post-communist context, which is characterized by lack of censorship and political pluralism. The phenomenon of history politics became extremely visible in Central and Eastern Europe in the past decade, and remains central for political agenda in many countries of the regions. Each essay is a case study contributing to the knowledge about collective memory and political use of history, offering a new theoretical twist. The studies look at actors (from political parties to individual historians), institutions (museums, Institutes of National remembrance, special political commissions), methods, political rationale and motivations behind this phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aHistoriographyxPolitical aspectszEuropevCase studies. 7aHISTORY / Essays.2bisacsh  aPostcommunism, Historiography, Political studies, Collective memory, Memory politics.1 aAktürk, Şener, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAstrov, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCusco, Andrei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDumitru, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGyáni, Gábor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHimka, John-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanowski, Maciej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasianov, Georgiy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingsto